english:
  title: Eulogy for Minister Zhao, Defender of the Crown, Attendant of the Crown Prince's Household, Co-Administrator of State Affairs, General of the Upper Rank, Great Scholar of the Hall of Cultivated Learning, and Compiler of the National History
  author: Lee Gyeo-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas! On the third day of the ninth month in the eighth year of Zhenyou, Minister Zhao, Defender of the Crown and Co-Administrator, fell ill and passed into the beyond. His coffin lay in repose at his private residence, and on the twenty-eighth day of that month, he was laid to rest at the foot of a certain mountain, according to proper rites.

    The Minister's given name was Chong, his courtesy name Damyak. He was a man of Hengcheon. His father, whose name was Yeongin, rose to the position of Attendant of the Crown Prince's Household and was acclaimed in his time as a premier of great renown. From youth, the Minister cherished learning and excelled in the literary arts. At the age of twenty, he achieved the rank of Advanced Scholar through examination. Being the son of a ministerial house, he early entered the path of office, summoned into the Imperial Household. From his first post until he reached the third rank, he remained within the inner court for nearly three decades.

    In the sixth year of Zhenyou, he was appointed Grand Rector of the National Academy, Scholar of the Precious Literature Pavilion, and Director of Imperial Decrees, simultaneously holding the position of Hanlin Scholar. It was customary that attendants of the court did not hold positions in the literary bureau, so the Minister rejoiced, saying: "Though I have held many offices, never have I obtained a post in literary composition. That today I adorn the roster of lettered scholars accords perfectly with my wish." From this time forward, he devoted himself even more intensely to the study of classical texts and histories, exerting all his efforts in the craft of writing. All important state documents and edicts flowed from his hand.

    Soon he was promoted to Minister of Rites, then advanced to Vice Minister of the Privy Council, Hanlin Scholar of Preeminent Rank. The Emperor, recognizing in the Minister talents both of the literary and martial kind, specially appointed him General of the Upper Rank. That a civil official should hold the concurrent rank of Upper General was a practice that began with the First Minister Wen Kexian and had long fallen into disuse—until it was revived through this Minister.

    At that time, the Khitans violated our borders. The Emperor appointed the Prime Minister of Yangcheng as Supreme Commander, with our Minister as Deputy Commander. They took up positions in Jiangxi. Shortly thereafter, the Supreme Commander was impeached for his mismanagement of the military, and the Minister, by regulation, was also dismissed—though in truth this was no fault of his. The following year he was restored to office as Keeper of the Privy Seal, Left Deputy of the Three Excellencies, Gentleman of the Council Chamber, and Great Scholar of the Hall of Cultivated Learning.

    As the invaders grew more fierce and our officers proved too weak to restrain them, the court again entrusted the Minister with command. With military ordinances enforced with perfect clarity, not even the smallest violation occurred. The enemy, their courage broken, retreated into the Jiangdong region and fortified themselves. At this time, the Tatars and the Kingdom of Dongzhen launched a great military incursion, claiming to break the Khitan forces and rescue our realm. Yet the Tatars are the most savage of all barbarian peoples, with no history of friendly relations with our kingdom. Both within and without the court, there was great alarm and doubt as to their true intentions. Courtly deliberations wavered; no response was sent. The embassy of courtesy was thus delayed.

    The Minister alone perceived that the circumstances gave no cause for suspicion. He repeatedly urged dispatch of an envoy. The Tatar commander grew wrathful at the delay and issued sharp rebukes. The Minister, adapting to circumstances and responding with discretion, swiftly brought about reconciliation. It was only after considerable time that the court's approval finally arrived.

    It is the Tatar custom to skewer morsels of meat on their sword points and feed them to others without pause. All our men showed discomfort at this practice. When the Tatar commander offered meat in this manner to the Minister, the Minister accepted it with perfect composure, as though it were his lifelong habit.

    The Tatar commander was also a great drinker. He proposed to compete with the Minister in drinking, with the loser to forfeit a wager. The Minister would fill his cup and drain it in one gulp, and though many cups passed his lips, no sign of drunkenness appeared. When the final cup was offered, the Minister set it down and spoke thus: "It is not that I cannot drink. But if I should prevail and the wager be exacted, you would necessarily suffer the penalty. Would it be right that a host should impose penalty upon his guest? Rather let me bear it." The commander, moved by these words, was greatly delighted and thereafter held the Minister in ever deeper esteem.

    When the commander encountered the generals and officers of Dongzhen and our own forces, he played with them freely, joking and jesting without restraint. Yet when he came before the Minister, though he showed affection and intimacy, he could not bring himself to be disrespectful. He proposed that the Minister be as an elder brother, granting him the place of honor. When the Minister deferred to him, saying such things were beneath him, the commander would respond: "My elder brother commands it—dare I not obey?" At their parting, the commander grasped the Minister's hand, tears streaming down his face, weeping with genuine emotion born not from mere show but from the heart.

    The commander of Dongzhen, being a keen judge of men, said to our people: "Your nation's general is a man of extraordinary and surpassing quality. That your realm possesses such a commander is a gift from Heaven." The Minister once, having drunk his fill, rested his head upon the commander's knee and fell asleep. The Dongzhen commander, fearing to wake him, remained perfectly still, not moving in the slightest. When his attendants requested that a pillow be substituted, the commander refused entirely.

    O marvel! In ancient times, there were true sages capable of taming fierce tigers and subduing poisonous serpents. The Tatars are beasts, their wickedness no less savage than tigers or serpents. Yet the Minister subdued them utterly through his rectitude and good faith. Was it not that his loyalty, righteousness, and trustworthy virtue could move even those of alien kind, as the true sages of old?

    When the barbarian threat was pacified, the Minister returned to take the position of Defender of the Crown, Attendant of the Crown Prince's Household, Co-Administrator of State Affairs, and Compiler of the National History. He passed away at the age of fifty.

    The Minister was a man of imposing stature and dignified bearing, with a generous spirit within. He was widely learned with a powerful memory, deeply versed in historical precedent and ancient custom. Early in his career he received high honors and served in positions of great responsibility. Three times he oversaw the examination of scholars at the National Academy, and all whom he selected became renowned figures of his age. In his dealings with scholars, regardless of rank, he dispensed with all formality and hierarchy. When scholars came to pay their respects, he would set out wine and ensure their complete enjoyment, making this his constant practice. The scholars of the time vied to seek his patronage, and no minister of his era was so renowned for his hospitality.

    In his daily administration, he never displayed sharp edges or rigid angles. Thus the world knew him only as magnanimous, broad-minded, and sage—yet failed to perceive the full measure of his inner reserves. Only when he wielded great armies and faced great affairs did his true nature become manifest: a spirit of boundless scope, filling heaven and earth, magnanimous and far from ordinary.

    Yet even this was but a minor aspect of the Minister's excellence. Had Heaven granted him a few more years of life, who could say whether his achievements and renown might not have been ten thousand times greater?

    Upon hearing of his passing, the Emperor was deeply grieved. He ordered officials to oversee the funeral rites and suspended court audiences for three days. The Emperor granted him the posthumous name "Minister Wenzhen" and commanded that a eulogy be composed to illuminate his virtues.

    **The Eulogy:**

    Stone gates locked with iron,
    Walls firm and towering high—
    Double doors and nested chambers,
    Palaces austere and deep.
    Shall we call this a nation?
    The Master said: "This is not so.

    A wise man must stand forth with authority,
    Like our noble Minister of the Crown.
    His bearing graced the council halls,
    His counsel shaped our statecraft.
    When he marched forth as commander,
    His orders, strict and absolute,
    Shook the alien tribes as wind shakes leaves.
    Then, and only then, may we speak of peace,
    And truly call it nation.

    Where tigers prowl in mountain depths,
    No one gathers the wild herbs.
    Where worthy men serve the state,
    Neighbors and enemies alike withdraw.

    Magnificent, our Minister—
    The nation's pillar, its foundation stone!
    With golden axe and crimson banner raised,
    His martial might shook all the western lands.

    The Tatars, fierce and unyielding,
    With tempers sharp as wolves and tigers—
    One slight provocation brought their wrath,
    Yet the Minister, through benevolence and faith,
    Laid bare his very heart.
    The beast-heart understood and felt compassion.
    They wept in love and longing.
    Without the Minister's strength,
    Our people would have been devoured.
    He gave us life, preserving head and body both.
    Our realm's great legacy, he renewed and restored.

    Yet Heaven granted no further days.
    The mandate came too soon.

    Alas, our Minister!
    You departed far too early.
    You came to serve the people—
    Why did you leave so suddenly?

    From the highest ministers to common folk,
    From children to the aged,
    All gathered with clasped hands,
    All mourned without exception.
    When a pillar of state is lost,
    The Emperor's grief knows no bounds.

    Honored in life, honored in death,
    With rites most solemn and abundant,
    His tomb shall shine with radiance below.

    Thus the Emperor bade me compose this eulogy
    To illuminate the Minister's virtue and grace.
    I, your servant, bow respectfully,
    Gather the fragrance he left behind,
    And with these humble words
    Seek to make his glory eternal.
